;B[rs]LB[pr:1][qr:2][os:3][rs:4]C[Dia.1 A hasty move

White's throw in at 1 is a little hasty in this case.  When Black plays at 2 White takes away an eye with 3 but then Black makes two eyes with 4.  If you play 3 at 4 then Black will play at 3 and live big.  3 and 4 are matbogi.
\lang1042\f1\fs18
])
(;AW[pp][qp][rp][sp][mq][nq][oq][mr][ms][ns][ss]AB[pq][qq][rq][sq][nr][or][rr][ps]
;W[os]
;B[pr]LB[os:1][pr:2]C[Dia.2 An endgame move

White 1 is just a plain and simple endgame move.  This is one of the common mistakes in beginner games.  Black connects and lives with 2.  Let's move on.
\lang1042\f1\fs18

])
(;AW[pp][qp][rp][sp][mq][nq][oq][mr][ms][ns][ss]AB[pq][qq][rq][sq][nr][or][rr][ps]
;W[rs]
;B[qs]
;W[pr]LB[rs:1][qs:2][pr:3]C[Dia.3 Correct

White 1 is the vital point as it attacks Black from the inside.  Now we see where Black's shortage of liberties come in.  When Black blocks at 2, White can throw in at 3 and now Black cannot connect.  There's no way for Black to live, right?  If Black 2 and 3, then you get bent four in the corner.
\lang1042\f1\fs18

